  "Ray- Could Stryd‚Äôs software work with accelerometers from other locations, such as the Tickr X or even runScribe‚Äôs shoe accelerometer? Is Stryd talking with any other companies about using their software/algorithms without a shorts-mounted accelerometer?",
  "I think people are going too far in the ‚Äúestimator‚Äù side. IMHO, using HR data is estimating with a dash of intelligence. This is measuring your actual motion in 3D space in real time and calculating the work required to achieve that motion. And if their algorithms for doing that are verifiable against force-plate treadmills, then it‚Äôs not ‚Äúestimation‚Äù, I don‚Äôt think. ‚ÄìDonnie",
  "Donnie, thanks for this very insightful comment. Your simple explanation of how the Stryd device works makes complete sense. And it also addresses some of the other comments above about whether the device would also require other sensors such as a barometer and wind sensor. If your explanation is correct, then clearly it would not need any of these other sensors ‚Äì just the accelerometer.",
  "Correct. The only thing HR is‚Ä¶ is a measurement of your body‚Äôs to work, not the actual work itself. Since the reaction is delayed, it‚Äôs often too little, too late. But if you‚Äôre familiar with what your body‚Äôs reaction to known work is (from training), you can keep an eye on the work and never let the reaction happen. If you know that you blow up after doing 250 watts for 2 hours, then you can avoid the blow up by staying at 245. The combination of the two is where the magic happens. You learn how your body reacts to specific work, then use that knowledge in races and also to measure improvements to see if a training method is working.",
  "Well, what matters is the ‚Äúmeasurement of your body‚Äôs to work‚Äù, to avoid blow up and get the best score possible, isn‚Äôt it ? This tool could still be usefull but has to be combined with slope, wind, stride (3D ?), HR, posture data to give you hints on your technical mistake of the moment and improve efficiency (because running implies more motion liberties than cycling). If not, that is just an ‚Äúaverage suffer score‚Äù based on weight and some accelerations. I don‚Äôt see how that could help improve running efficiency or avoid blow up during a race. anyway, I have both tickr run and garmin‚Äôs HR+accelerometers strap, just have to wait the first one to implement that kind of ‚Äúsuffer score‚Äù around ‚Ä¶",
  "‚Äù calculating the work required to achieve that motion‚Äù. But that‚Äôs not what you want. Running along a flat at a constant pace, the total work being done is zero because you‚Äôre not accelerating so there‚Äôs no net force (F = ma). There are other forces operating than the ones you produce with your feet, and they do work, too. What you want is how much power you need to generate with your muscles to offset the power being lost to external factors. Air resistance would be one, but primarily for runners it just seems to be the power lost as your feet convert motion into heat as they slap the ground. On grades, then gravity comes into play, but that‚Äôs well understood and the power gain/loss is linear in the vertical speed. But it can‚Äôt be as simple as just using the measured acceleration, because most of the time that‚Äôs going to be zero.",
  "‚ÄúRunning along a flat at a constant pace, the total work being done is zero because you‚Äôre not accelerating so there‚Äôs no net force (F = ma).‚Äù I don‚Äôt think you understand how running works, it isn‚Äôt a constant pace along a flat. Running is launching yourself forward into the air with one foot then landing with the other before launching again over and over and over.",
